00:39:33.040 --> 00:39:36.040
Alright, yet another concept for part nine.

00:39:36.040 --> 00:39:39.040
And this one, this is a tricky one.

00:39:39.040 --> 00:39:41.040
So bear with me.

00:39:42.040 --> 00:39:46.040
For each aesthetic...

00:39:48.040 --> 00:39:51.040
Each aesthetic mapping, I should say,

00:39:51.040 --> 00:39:54.040
there's this translation going on

00:39:54.040 --> 00:39:57.040
from values in your data frame

00:39:57.040 --> 00:40:02.040
to something that appears in your data visualization.

00:40:02.040 --> 00:40:05.040
And there's not always...

00:40:05.040 --> 00:40:10.040
There's almost never a one-to-one relationship.

00:40:11.040 --> 00:40:17.040
Somehow, part nine has to convert those raw values into pixels.

00:40:17.040 --> 00:40:20.040
So that's what this mapping is all about.

00:40:20.040 --> 00:40:24.040
And this is influenced by many things.

00:40:25.040 --> 00:40:28.040
So, relatively speaking,

00:40:28.040 --> 00:40:33.040
when the x value in a data frame

00:40:33.040 --> 00:40:35.040
related to a certain data,

00:40:35.040 --> 00:40:39.040
related to a certain row, is higher,

00:40:39.040 --> 00:40:42.040
the corresponding point in the data visualization

00:40:42.040 --> 00:40:45.040
moves to the right.

00:40:46.040 --> 00:40:48.040
But by how much?

00:40:48.040 --> 00:40:52.040
That's determined by a number of things.

00:40:52.040 --> 00:40:55.040
First of all, it's determined by, well,

00:40:55.040 --> 00:40:58.040
where do we start this x-axis?

00:40:58.040 --> 00:41:01.040
Does it start at zero?

00:41:01.040 --> 00:41:03.040
And what is the end?

00:41:03.040 --> 00:41:05.040
And what is the...

00:41:05.040 --> 00:41:07.040
Is it linear?

00:41:07.040 --> 00:41:10.040
Or is it on a log scale?

00:41:12.040 --> 00:41:15.040
So, this can be influenced

00:41:15.040 --> 00:41:20.040
using a collection of functions

00:41:20.040 --> 00:41:23.040
that start with the word scale.

00:41:23.040 --> 00:41:25.040
And there is a scale.

00:41:25.040 --> 00:41:29.040
There are scales for every aesthetic out there.

00:41:29.040 --> 00:41:31.040
So in this particular example,

00:41:31.040 --> 00:41:36.040
what I've done is I have turned the x-axis

00:41:37.040 --> 00:41:39.040
into a log scale.

00:41:39.040 --> 00:41:44.040
Using the function scale underscore x underscore log 10.

00:41:46.040 --> 00:41:49.040
And for the y-axis,

00:41:49.040 --> 00:41:51.040
well, I kept the type of scale,

00:41:51.040 --> 00:41:53.040
which is by default,

00:41:53.040 --> 00:41:55.040
there's always a default,

00:41:55.040 --> 00:41:58.040
and for x and y scales continuous,

00:41:58.040 --> 00:42:01.040
I changed the limits.

00:42:01.040 --> 00:42:03.040
So, by default,

00:42:03.040 --> 00:42:06.040
those limits are based on the data,

00:42:06.040 --> 00:42:08.040
on the lowest value and on the highest value,

00:42:08.040 --> 00:42:10.040
and then some.

00:42:10.040 --> 00:42:12.040
But you can apply those.

00:42:12.040 --> 00:42:13.040
So here, I said, okay, now,

00:42:13.040 --> 00:42:17.040
I absolutely want my y-axis to start at zero

00:42:17.040 --> 00:42:20.040
and to end at 20.

00:42:20.040 --> 00:42:24.040
But scales go beyond the location

00:42:24.040 --> 00:42:28.040
of a point or of any geometry.

00:42:28.040 --> 00:42:30.040
Like I said, there is a scale

00:42:30.040 --> 00:42:33.040
for every aesthetic.

00:42:33.040 --> 00:42:35.040
There's also color, right?

00:42:35.040 --> 00:42:40.040
But mine has to translate raw data values

00:42:40.040 --> 00:42:42.040
into some color.

00:42:42.040 --> 00:42:46.040
And depending on the type of the column

00:42:46.040 --> 00:42:50.040
and depending on what you want to convey,

00:42:50.040 --> 00:42:52.040
this can be different.

00:42:54.040 --> 00:42:56.040
What I've done here is

00:42:56.040 --> 00:43:00.040
I've used a different, yeah, column map.

00:43:00.040 --> 00:43:04.040
These come from the Brewer collection

00:43:04.040 --> 00:43:06.040
of palettes, so to speak.

00:43:06.040 --> 00:43:10.040
So these take some very particular arguments,

00:43:10.040 --> 00:43:12.040
so the type and the palette.

00:43:14.040 --> 00:43:16.040
And what you're doing here, then,

00:43:16.040 --> 00:43:18.040
is you override the colors

00:43:18.040 --> 00:43:23.040
that are being used for data sets.

00:43:24.040 --> 00:43:28.040
This is, of course, a discrete column,

00:43:28.040 --> 00:43:30.040
the quality of it.

00:43:30.040 --> 00:43:34.040
But if you have a continuous value,

00:43:34.040 --> 00:43:36.040
you might only use a gradient.

00:43:39.040 --> 00:43:41.040
And also for the size,

00:43:41.040 --> 00:43:45.040
it's a bit contrived in this example,

00:43:45.040 --> 00:43:50.040
but it does help me make my point here

00:43:50.040 --> 00:43:53.040
in that the size of each point

00:43:53.040 --> 00:43:57.040
is also determined by the values

00:43:57.040 --> 00:43:59.040
in the Y column.

00:43:59.040 --> 00:44:01.040
So that's a little bit redundant,

00:44:01.040 --> 00:44:03.040
because we're already using Y

00:44:03.040 --> 00:44:05.040
for the Y axis.

00:44:05.040 --> 00:44:08.040
So what I've done here is

00:44:08.040 --> 00:44:10.040
I have said, okay,

00:44:12.040 --> 00:44:16.040
the minimum value

00:44:16.040 --> 00:44:18.040
that I am going to consider

00:44:18.040 --> 00:44:20.040
in the raw data

00:44:20.040 --> 00:44:22.040
that will determine the size

00:44:22.040 --> 00:44:24.040
of each point is 5.

00:44:25.040 --> 00:44:27.040
Right, so if the value of Y

00:44:27.040 --> 00:44:29.040
is below that,

00:44:29.040 --> 00:44:31.040
it gets the same size.

00:44:32.040 --> 00:44:34.040
And same thing,

00:44:34.040 --> 00:44:37.040
the upper limit is 10.

00:44:38.040 --> 00:44:41.040
So the points are very, very small here,

00:44:41.040 --> 00:44:43.040
but you might be able to see

00:44:43.040 --> 00:44:45.040
that any data point,

00:44:45.040 --> 00:44:47.040
and there are four of them,

00:44:47.040 --> 00:44:49.040
that are 10,

00:44:49.040 --> 00:44:51.040
that have a value of 10 or higher

00:44:51.040 --> 00:44:53.040
on the Y axis,

00:44:53.040 --> 00:44:55.040
all have the same size.

00:44:56.040 --> 00:44:58.040
And the range there,

00:44:58.040 --> 00:45:00.040
that's the second argument of this

00:45:00.040 --> 00:45:02.040
scale size continuous function,

00:45:02.040 --> 00:45:04.040
determines, okay, what is then

00:45:04.040 --> 00:45:07.040
the actual size being used?

00:45:08.040 --> 00:45:11.040
So how small should the smallest point be,

00:45:11.040 --> 00:45:14.040
and how large should the largest point be?

00:45:14.040 --> 00:45:17.040
So, conceptually speaking,

00:45:17.040 --> 00:45:19.040
what we're doing here is

00:45:19.040 --> 00:45:23.040
we're mapping raw data values

00:45:23.040 --> 00:45:25.040
onto some aesthetic values,

00:45:25.040 --> 00:45:27.040
and that translation,

00:45:27.040 --> 00:45:30.040
that's what we're influencing right here.

00:45:32.040 --> 00:45:34.040
So limits and range,

00:45:34.040 --> 00:45:36.040
it differs a little bit per scale

00:45:36.040 --> 00:45:38.040
on which arguments are being used,

00:45:39.040 --> 00:45:41.040
but this is the case,

00:45:41.040 --> 00:45:43.040
the range and limit is the case

00:45:43.040 --> 00:45:46.040
for scale size continuous.

00:45:47.040 --> 00:45:50.040
There is definitely consistency there.

00:45:52.040 --> 00:45:54.040
Don't worry.

00:45:56.040 --> 00:45:59.040
And this is, I found this at least to be

00:45:59.040 --> 00:46:01.040
the toughest concept

00:46:01.040 --> 00:46:03.040
to wrap my head around.

