Like, this would be like a chain of operations,

00:46:22.040 --> 00:46:24.040
where you just start with this operation,

00:46:24.040 --> 00:46:27.040
and you don't really need to add.

00:46:27.040 --> 00:46:30.040
Is it adding layers on top of it?

00:46:32.040 --> 00:46:33.040
All right.

00:46:33.040 --> 00:46:34.040
Yeah.

00:46:34.040 --> 00:46:36.040
So to summarize your question,

00:46:36.040 --> 00:46:38.040
what's up with that plus sign?

00:46:39.040 --> 00:46:41.040
And this is, again, this is history,

00:46:41.040 --> 00:46:45.040
because that's how R's ggplug does things.

00:46:45.040 --> 00:46:48.040
This plus operator has been overloaded,

00:46:48.040 --> 00:46:51.040
and nowadays,

00:46:51.040 --> 00:46:53.040
if you're familiar with R and the tidyverse,

00:46:53.040 --> 00:46:55.040
you use the pipe operator

00:46:55.040 --> 00:46:57.040
to combine things.

00:46:58.040 --> 00:47:01.040
And in Python, we're used to do method checking.

00:47:02.040 --> 00:47:06.040
But since Hasan wanted to stay close

00:47:06.040 --> 00:47:08.040
to the original API,

00:47:09.040 --> 00:47:11.040
he used the plus operator.

00:47:11.040 --> 00:47:13.040
And indeed, what you said, right?

00:47:13.040 --> 00:47:15.040
You're adding layers,

00:47:15.040 --> 00:47:19.040
but only certain functions add layers.

00:47:19.040 --> 00:47:23.040
So those who start with geom add layers,

00:47:23.040 --> 00:47:25.040
and there's also, there's a couple of others,

00:47:25.040 --> 00:47:27.040
but that's outside the scope of this tutorial.

00:47:27.040 --> 00:47:32.040
But everything else also gets added,

00:47:32.040 --> 00:47:34.040
but it's not technically a layer

00:47:34.040 --> 00:47:36.040
that you're then adding.

00:47:37.040 --> 00:47:39.040
So conceptually, it's like method changing,

00:47:39.040 --> 00:47:41.040
only a different syntax,

00:47:41.040 --> 00:47:44.040
and I know that takes some getting used to.

00:47:44.040 --> 00:47:47.040
But trust me, you will be able to get used to that,

00:47:47.040 --> 00:47:49.040
just by using that.

00:47:50.040 --> 00:47:51.040
Yeah.

