Okay.

00:59:02.040 --> 00:59:04.040
The fifth concept

00:59:04.040 --> 00:59:06.040
that you need to wrap your head around.

00:59:06.040 --> 00:59:08.040
Layers and inheritance.

00:59:08.040 --> 00:59:09.040
And we already had a question

00:59:09.040 --> 00:59:11.040
related to this.

00:59:13.040 --> 00:59:14.040
Remember,

00:59:14.040 --> 00:59:15.040
we had a question

00:59:15.040 --> 00:59:16.040
as in,

00:59:16.040 --> 00:59:17.040
why do I see

00:59:17.040 --> 00:59:18.040
the ADS function

00:59:18.040 --> 00:59:19.040
being used

00:59:19.040 --> 00:59:21.040
multiple times?

00:59:21.040 --> 00:59:22.040
So,

00:59:22.040 --> 00:59:24.040
first of all, layers.

00:59:24.040 --> 00:59:26.040
Every geom function

00:59:26.040 --> 00:59:28.040
Every geom function

00:59:28.040 --> 00:59:30.040
creates a new layer.

00:59:30.040 --> 00:59:32.040
And the order here matters.

00:59:32.040 --> 00:59:33.040
The one you specify first

00:59:33.040 --> 00:59:35.040
gets drawn first.

00:59:37.040 --> 00:59:38.040
And,

00:59:39.040 --> 00:59:40.040
the

00:59:40.040 --> 00:59:42.040
inheritance part here

00:59:42.040 --> 00:59:43.040
refers to

00:59:43.040 --> 00:59:45.040
both the data

00:59:45.040 --> 00:59:47.040
and the aesthetics mapping.

00:59:47.040 --> 00:59:49.040
These are two things

00:59:49.040 --> 00:59:51.040
that we can specify

00:59:51.040 --> 00:59:53.040
in the ggplot function.

00:59:53.040 --> 00:59:55.040
Our constructor, so to speak.

00:59:56.040 --> 00:59:58.040
And when you specify them

00:59:58.040 --> 01:00:00.040
at this top level,

01:00:00.040 --> 01:00:02.040
then all the layers

01:00:02.040 --> 01:00:04.040
will inherit both

01:00:04.040 --> 01:00:06.040
the data and the aesthetics mapping.

01:00:07.040 --> 01:00:08.040
And this is,

01:00:08.040 --> 01:00:09.040
for a lot of cases,

01:00:09.040 --> 01:00:11.040
this is quite convenient.

01:00:11.040 --> 01:00:12.040
Right?

01:00:13.040 --> 01:00:14.040
You don't need to specify

01:00:14.040 --> 01:00:16.040
which data frame you want to use

01:00:16.040 --> 01:00:18.040
for every layer separately.

01:00:18.040 --> 01:00:19.040
But you can,

01:00:19.040 --> 01:00:21.040
if you want to.

01:00:21.040 --> 01:00:23.040
Sometimes you do want to use

01:00:23.040 --> 01:00:25.040
a different data frame

01:00:25.040 --> 01:00:27.040
for another layer.

01:00:27.040 --> 01:00:28.040
Think about,

01:00:28.040 --> 01:00:29.040
okay, so,

01:00:29.040 --> 01:00:30.040
bear with me here,

01:00:30.040 --> 01:00:31.040
but you have

01:00:31.040 --> 01:00:32.040
a scatterplot.

01:00:32.040 --> 01:00:33.040
Right?

01:00:33.040 --> 01:00:34.040
With a couple of clusters.

01:00:34.040 --> 01:00:36.040
And you also have some labels.

01:00:36.040 --> 01:00:37.040
Some text.

01:00:37.040 --> 01:00:38.040
And you want,

01:00:38.040 --> 01:00:39.040
at the center

01:00:39.040 --> 01:00:41.040
of each cluster,

01:00:41.040 --> 01:00:43.040
to have a single label.

01:00:44.040 --> 01:00:45.040
Now,

01:00:45.040 --> 01:00:47.040
the labels need to come from

01:00:47.040 --> 01:00:48.040
a separate data frame

01:00:48.040 --> 01:00:50.040
that only has a few rows.

01:00:50.040 --> 01:00:51.040
One row per cluster.

01:00:51.040 --> 01:00:53.040
So you have to do some

01:00:54.040 --> 01:00:56.040
some aggregation.

01:00:56.040 --> 01:00:58.040
Or maybe even some clustering yourself.

01:00:58.040 --> 01:01:00.040
But then you are able

01:01:00.040 --> 01:01:02.040
to add a new layer

01:01:02.040 --> 01:01:04.040
using geom text,

01:01:04.040 --> 01:01:05.040
geom label.

01:01:05.040 --> 01:01:06.040
Right?

01:01:06.040 --> 01:01:07.040
Add those labels.

01:01:07.040 --> 01:01:08.040
And say,

01:01:08.040 --> 01:01:09.040
okay,

01:01:09.040 --> 01:01:10.040
I don't want you to use

01:01:10.040 --> 01:01:11.040
the default data set

01:01:11.040 --> 01:01:13.040
that contains all the data points.

01:01:13.040 --> 01:01:15.040
I want you to use this other

01:01:15.040 --> 01:01:16.040
small data frame

01:01:16.040 --> 01:01:18.040
which just contains

01:01:18.040 --> 01:01:20.040
the labels

01:01:20.040 --> 01:01:21.040
and the coordinates

01:01:21.040 --> 01:01:23.040
where they should be put.

01:01:26.040 --> 01:01:27.040
So that's for the data.

01:01:27.040 --> 01:01:29.040
And then for the aesthetics,

01:01:29.040 --> 01:01:31.040
same story.

01:01:33.040 --> 01:01:34.040
Sometimes,

01:01:36.040 --> 01:01:38.040
not every layer

01:01:38.040 --> 01:01:39.040
has to have

01:01:39.040 --> 01:01:41.040
every aesthetics mapping.

01:01:42.040 --> 01:01:44.040
Coming back again to labels.

01:01:44.040 --> 01:01:45.040
Right?

01:01:45.040 --> 01:01:46.040
For a label,

01:01:46.040 --> 01:01:47.040
you need to specify,

01:01:47.040 --> 01:01:48.040
okay,

01:01:48.040 --> 01:01:49.040
in which column

01:01:49.040 --> 01:01:50.040
do we have the text?

01:01:50.040 --> 01:01:51.040
Right?

01:01:52.040 --> 01:01:53.040
And that's always specific,

01:01:53.040 --> 01:01:55.040
that's very specific

01:01:55.040 --> 01:01:57.040
for all the geometries,

01:01:57.040 --> 01:01:58.040
text and labels.

01:01:58.040 --> 01:01:59.040
So,

01:01:59.040 --> 01:02:01.040
what I usually do is

01:02:01.040 --> 01:02:03.040
I reuse

01:02:03.040 --> 01:02:05.040
the AES function

01:02:05.040 --> 01:02:06.040
and only add

01:02:06.040 --> 01:02:08.040
that specific mapping.

01:02:15.040 --> 01:02:17.040
Something that I haven't really included

01:02:17.040 --> 01:02:18.040
in this presentation,

01:02:18.040 --> 01:02:19.040
but,

01:02:19.040 --> 01:02:20.040
I don't know,

01:02:20.040 --> 01:02:21.040
I don't hear any questions about it,

01:02:21.040 --> 01:02:23.040
but I do want to

01:02:23.040 --> 01:02:24.040
point it out,

01:02:24.040 --> 01:02:26.040
is this facet rep function.

01:02:27.040 --> 01:02:28.040
I've already shown it a couple of times,

01:02:28.040 --> 01:02:29.040
but I've never

01:02:29.040 --> 01:02:30.040
really, you know,

01:02:30.040 --> 01:02:31.040
explained it to you.

01:02:31.040 --> 01:02:32.040
Well,

01:02:32.040 --> 01:02:33.040
what this does,

01:02:33.040 --> 01:02:34.040
it creates facets.

01:02:34.040 --> 01:02:36.040
It creates these four panels,

01:02:37.040 --> 01:02:38.040
one for each data set,

01:02:38.040 --> 01:02:40.040
one for each unique value

01:02:40.040 --> 01:02:42.040
in the data set column,

01:02:42.040 --> 01:02:43.040
which is all

01:02:43.040 --> 01:02:44.040
the Roman numerals

01:02:44.040 --> 01:02:46.040
one through four.

01:02:47.040 --> 01:02:48.040
And,

01:02:48.040 --> 01:02:49.040
I think this is,

01:02:49.040 --> 01:02:50.040
this really captures the idea

01:02:50.040 --> 01:02:52.040
that you use

01:02:52.040 --> 01:02:54.040
plotline in a declarative way.

01:02:54.040 --> 01:02:55.040
Right?

01:02:56.040 --> 01:02:58.040
You're not programming this

01:02:58.040 --> 01:03:00.040
procedurally or anything.

01:03:00.040 --> 01:03:02.040
You specify

01:03:02.040 --> 01:03:04.040
what you want to visualize,

01:03:04.040 --> 01:03:05.040
and then plotline

01:03:05.040 --> 01:03:07.040
will figure out how to do it.

01:03:14.040 --> 01:03:16.040
Okay, so related to this,

01:03:16.040 --> 01:03:17.040
is it related?

01:03:17.040 --> 01:03:19.040
It's related enough that I've

01:03:19.040 --> 01:03:21.040
packed it into one exercise.

01:03:21.040 --> 01:03:22.040
So,

01:03:23.040 --> 01:03:25.040
this is the last concept.

01:03:30.040 --> 01:03:31.040
There are,

01:03:31.040 --> 01:03:33.040
so we've talked about these aesthetics, right?

01:03:33.040 --> 01:03:35.040
Properties that

01:03:35.040 --> 01:03:37.040
influence how a

01:03:37.040 --> 01:03:39.040
geometry is being drawn.

01:03:40.040 --> 01:03:41.040
Most of the time,

01:03:41.040 --> 01:03:43.040
we want these to be based

01:03:43.040 --> 01:03:44.040
on our data, right?

01:03:44.040 --> 01:03:45.040
Because we're creating

01:03:45.040 --> 01:03:47.040
data visualizations.

01:03:48.040 --> 01:03:50.040
Sometimes you want things to be

01:03:50.040 --> 01:03:51.040
static.

01:03:51.040 --> 01:03:52.040
You want to

01:03:52.040 --> 01:03:54.040
set a certain

01:03:54.040 --> 01:03:55.040
aesthetic

